04557nam a22006615i 9780804793131DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20202014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2014029030  a97808047931317 a10.1515/97808047931312doi  a(DE-B1597)563681  a(OCoLC)1224277995  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aPJ5053.B7bZ83413 2015 4aPJ5053.B7bZ83413 2015 7aHIS0190002bisacsh04a892.43/52231 aShapira, Anita, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aYosef Haim Brenner :bA Life /cAnita Shapira. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (488 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Jewish History and C00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- t1. The Emergence of a Writer, 1881-1901 -- t2. In the Imperial Russian Army, 1901-1904 -- t3. London, 1904-1906 -- t4. London, 1906-1908 -- t5. Lvov, 1908-1909 -- t6. In Palestine, 1909-1911 -- t7. The Jerusalem Years, 1911-1914 -- t8. Wartime, 1914-1918 -- t9. Under British Rule, 1918-1921 -- t10. Days in May, 1921 -- t11. De Mortuis -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBased on previously unexploited primary sources, this is the first comprehensive biography of Yosef Haim Brenner, one of the pioneers of Modern Hebrew literature. Born in 1881 to a poor Jewish family in Russia, Brenner published his first story, "A Loaf of Bread," in 1900. After being drafted into the Russian army, he deserted to England and later immigrated to Palestine where he became an eminent writer, critic and cultural icon of the Jewish and Zionist cultural milieu. His life was tragically ended in the violent 1921 Jaffa riots. In a nutshell, Brenner's life story encompasses the generation that made "the great leap" from Imperial Russia's Pale of Settlement to the metropolitan centers of modernity, and from traditional Jewish beliefs and way of life to secularism and existentialism. In his writing he experimented with language and form, but always attempting to portray life realistically. A highly acerbic critic of Jewish society, Brenner was relentless in portraying the vices of both Jewish public life and individual Jews. Most of his contemporaries not only accepted his critique, but admired him for his forthrightness and took it as evidence of his honesty and veracity. Renowned author and historian Anita Shapira's new biography illuminates Brenner's life and times, and his relationships with leading cultural leaders such as Nobel laureate S.Y. Agnon, Hayim Nahman Bialik, Israel's National Poet, and many others. Undermining the accepted myths about his life and his death, his depression, his relations with writers, women, and men-including the question of his homoeroticism-this new biography examines Brenner's life in all its complexity and contradiction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAuthors, HebrewvBiography. 0aZionistsvBiography. 4aBrenner. 4aHebrew renaissance. 4aJewish culture. 4aJewish nationalism. 4aLvov. 4aPale of Settlement. 4aPalestine. 4aYiddish language and literature. 4aZionism. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh1 aBerris, Anthony08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804793131zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804793131423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804793131.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles